Yataththawala Bodhiwansaramaya Rajamaha Viharaya
Yataththawala Bodhiwansaramaya Rajamaha Viharaya is an ancient Buddhist temple belonging to the era of the Dambadeniya kingdom with a Tampita Viharaya belonging to the Kandyan Era. The temple lies between Madampe and Narammala and 9 km off Kuliyapitiya. To reach the temple from Kuliyapitiya, travel 2 km towards Narammala to reach Laduyaya junction. Take the 
 road for about 5 km and take the left fork at the 
 Junction. The temple lies about 3 km away from this junction.
A Tampita Viharaya is a structure built on a wooden platform which rests on number of stone stumps usually 3-4 feet tall. The roof is held by a structure built of timber and the walls are generally made of wattle and daub. Walls inside the chamber is more or less always covered in paintings drawn mainly in Kandyan style.
This Tampita Viharaya along with the Hevisi Mandapaya was declared as an protected archaeological monument by the gazette dated 24th July 2009 and describes it as follows ;
“The Tampita Image House (Image House built on stone piles) and Hewisi Mandapaya belonging to the Yataththawela Bodhiwansarama Purana Viharaya premises situated in No. 532 Yataththawela Grama Niladhari Division in the Pannala Divisional Secretary’s Division, Kurunegala District, North Western Province.”
